<section>
  <p class="eyebrow">Speaker A · exact canon excerpt</p>
  <h2>Article Three</h2>
  <blockquote class="reading"><p>Your speech¹ demonstrate your desired mode² of communication; As you've acted upon another, so you are demonstrated to consent to be thus acted upon, even in reciprocity.³</p></blockquote>
  <div class="grid">
    <article class="panel"><h3>Plain orientation</h3><p>Article Three says communication is not only content. Tone, clarity, courtesy, threat, insult, patience, and escalation all signal the rules of the interaction.</p></article>
    <article class="panel"><h3>Central tension</h3><p>The article can protect reciprocity, but it can also be misused as vengeance. Its useful form requires proportionality, context, and repair; otherwise reciprocity becomes excuse.</p></article>
  </div>
</section>
<section>
  <p class="eyebrow">Speaker B · footnote conversation</p>
  <h2>What the notes keep from collapsing</h2>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ¹ · speech</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> speak to be understood</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> makes communication responsible to reception, not merely expression. The goal is not just to speak, but to make meaning available.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ² · mode</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> courtesy never disimproved a situation</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> preserves courtesy as cheap risk reduction. It does not require submission; it reduces needless friction before conflict hardens.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ³ · reciprocity</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> an eye for an eye leaves the world blind, but a fist to the face might be kind&gt;</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> refuses both empty pacifism and gleeful retaliation. Some boundaries must be felt, but the burden is to stop harm, not enjoy escalation.</p></article>
