<section class="panel">
  <p class="eyebrow">Handbook seed</p>
  <h2>Chapter section: Speech as demonstrated consent</h2>
  <p>Article Three teaches that the form of communication matters. People often claim one intention while demonstrating another through method.</p>
  <p>A circle applying this article should identify the communication mode before judging the dispute. If someone uses contempt, intimidation, or bad-faith confusion, they have changed the conversation they are in.</p>
  <p>Still, reciprocity must remain bounded. The aim is to restore truthful interaction, not to license cruelty.</p>
</section>
<section class="panel">
  <p class="eyebrow">60–90 second script</p>
  <h2>Short video draft</h2>
  <p><strong>Title:</strong> Speak as though meaning matters</p>
  <p>Article Three says your speech demonstrates your desired mode of communication. That means how you speak is part of what you consent to.</p>
  <p>If you speak to be understood, you invite understanding. If you command, mock, threaten, or obscure, you are not in the same conversation.</p>
  <p>The article also says that as you have acted upon another, you demonstrate consent to be acted upon in reciprocity. That is dangerous if taken as revenge. It is useful when taken as responsibility: do not demand gentleness while practicing contempt.</p>
  <p>Courtesy never disimproved a situation. Clear speech is care. Reciprocal consequence is boundary. The work is to keep both from becoming domination.</p>
</section>
